"Onorato P., Mascheretti P., DeAmbrosis A.","'Home made' model to study the greenhouse effect and global warming",2011,"European Journal of Physics","32","2",,"363","376",,,10.1088/0143-0807/32/2/009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79951876751&partnerID=40&md5=0276f2467c258c792f19a871673988bf","Department of Physics 'A. Volta', University of Pavia, Via Bassi 6, I-27100 Pavia, Italy; INFN, Laboratori Nazionali di Frascati, PO Box 13, 00044 Frascati, Italy","Onorato, P., Department of Physics 'A. Volta', University of Pavia, Via Bassi 6, I-27100 Pavia, Italy, INFN, Laboratori Nazionali di Frascati, PO Box 13, 00044 Frascati, Italy; Mascheretti, P., Department of Physics 'A. Volta', University of Pavia, Via Bassi 6, I-27100 Pavia, Italy; DeAmbrosis, A., Department of Physics 'A. Volta', University of Pavia, Via Bassi 6, I-27100 Pavia, Italy","In this paper a simplified two-parameter model of the greenhouse effect on the Earth is developed, starting from the well known two-layer model. It allows both the analysis of the temperatures of the inner planets, by focusing on the role of the greenhouse effect, and a comparison between the temperatures the planets should have in the absence of greenhouse effect and their actual ones. It may also be used to predict the average temperature of the Earth surface in the future, depending on the variations of the concentration of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere due to human activities. This model can promote an elementary understanding of global warming since it allows a simple formalization of the energy balance for the Earth in the stationary condition, in the presence of greenhouse gases. For these reasons it can be introduced in courses for undergraduate physics students and for teacher preparation. ©2011 IOP Publishing Ltd.",,"Average temperature; Earth surface; Human activities; Stationary conditions; Teacher preparation; Two layer model; Two-parameter models; Atmospheric temperature; Carbon dioxide; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Greenhouses; Planets; Students; Teaching; Greenhouse effect",,,,,,"Besson, U., De Ambrosis, A., Mascheretti, P., Studying the physical basis of global warming: Thermal effects of the interaction between radiation and matter and greenhouse effect (2010) Eur. J. Phys., 31, pp. 375-388; Graedel, T.E., Crutzen, P.J., (1993) Atmospheric Change. An Earth System Perspective, , (New York: Freeman); Seinfeld, S.H., Pandis, S.N., (1998) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics. From Air Pollution to Climate Change, , (New York: Wiley); Turco, R.P., (1997) Earth Under Siege. From Air Pollution to Global Change, , (Oxford: Oxford University Press); Maslin, M., (2008) Global Warming: A Very Short Introduction, , 2nd edn (Oxford: Oxford University Press); Houghton, J.T., Jenkins, G.J., Ephraums, J.J., (1990) Climate Change: The IPCC Scientific Assessment, , (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press); Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Bruce, J., Lee, H., Callander, B.A., Haites, E., Harris, N., Maskell, K., (1995) Climate Change 1994: Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios, , (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press); Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Callender, B.A., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A., Maskell, K., (1996) Climate Change 1995: The Science of Climate Change, , (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press); Solomon, S., Qin, D., Manning, M., Chen, Z., Marquis, M., Averyt, K.B., Tignor, M., Miller, H.L., (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis Contribution ofWorking Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press); Fourier, J.B.J., (1827) Mem. de l'Ac. R. d. Sci. de l'Inst. de France T.7; Arrhenius, S., On the influence of carbonic acid in the air upon the temperature of the ground (1896) Phil. Mag., 41, pp. 237-276; Kiehl, J.T., Trenberth, K.E., Earth's annual globalmean energy budget (1997) Bull. Am.Meteorol. Soc